title: For Sale:  KSG shotgun
location: South of Charlotte, Charlotte, North Carolina
postcontent:
The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward.  The KSG weighs 6.9lbs and is as compact as legally possible with a 26.1" overall length and an 18.5" cylinder bore barrel.  Even with this compact size, the internal dual tube magazines hold an impressive 6 rounds of 12 gauge 3" shells each, for a total capacity of 6+6+1 (7 per tube if using 2-3/4" shells).  The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube.  The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.  The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine.  A cross bolt style safety blocks the sear, and the pump release lever is located in front of the trigger guard.

 The pump includes an under Picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, or a light or laser.  The included top Picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights.  Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included.  The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.

Ammo In a Can is a patented process that removes the atmosphere from inside the can and replaces it with dry, inert nitrogen gas. Without moisture or oxygen in the can, the ammunition does not deteriorate, corrode, or rust. This gives the ammo an indefinite shelf life, regardless of the environment outside the can. Accessories this rifle comes with:

This rifle is both highly accurate and a blast to shoot, I just simply don't use it enough compared my other rifles with regulated gas systems to justify keeping it in the safe.

title: For Sale:  1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model
postcontent:
This was Remington's very first repeating shotgun. Introduced in 1908 and discontinued in 1929. This is an amazing piece of history & one any serious shotgun collector needs in their collection. Made in November of 1923. Remington model 10-A, 26" barrel 12 ga, take down model. all numbers matching. Only 3500 of the 10-A were made. From what i have read, the 10-A models were used in WW2 by the USMC to train aerial gunners. For being 1 month short of it's 90th birthday this ol'timer is in remarkable unrestored/original condition. There is one smaller area of pitting on top of the receiver, but nothing too bad at all. It has 1 minor issue that prevents it from being used. A broken sear spring as seen in the pic below. It's a $10 part readily available online. The sear spring from a standard model 10 will interchange. I thought I wanted a shotgun, but that has changed so i'm really not interested in restoring it, but would rather just sell or trade it out for something i'll enjoy. 

Trades: what do you have? I'm open to just about anything.

I also want to ad this is a HUGE shotgun. In the pics below with me holding it, I'm 6'1" and 250lbs. I look like a kid holding 'daddys gun' ...lol. I picked this up a while back & have decided it's just not for me so i'm looking to trade out for something I will enjoy using. 

I'm open to anything except black powder weapons. My son and I collect vintage .22 rifles. His birthday is coming up next month and has been hinting at his interest in a single action .22 revolver I'd possibly be interested in something in that flavor. What do you have?

I'm unable to drive any longer so you would have to be willing to come to the Camdenton/Linn Creek area to pick this up.

title: For Sale:  New CMMG BCG
postcontent:
I am selling a new CMMG Auto Profile Bolt Carrier Group.  It's new in tube, and never fired.  They retail for $170, and I'll take $135 firm.  Here are the specs from CMMG:

Our 5.56 BCGs follow the mil-spec pretty closely. Dimension and tolerance wise they are absolutely mil-spec. We have deviated a little bit with regard to material and processes. 

Our carrier keys are Mil-Spec, made from a solid piece of 4130 steel, chrome lined and phosphated. 
Our carriers again are Mil-Spec M16 carriers. Made from 8620 steel, chrome lined and phosphated. 
The carriers are assembled using a more modern version of the mil-spec screw(the mil-spec screw uses a 1/8" hex verses the newer and more common 9/64" hex). On the note of screws ours and the Mil-Spec screws are the equivalent to Grade 8, SAE grades do not cover screws/bolts smaller than 1/4". The screws are installed using a torque wrench to ensure they are torqued correctly. The key and screws are then staked using our custom pneumatic staker. 

Now the bolts, they are made with AISI 9310 Steel, 9310 is better suited for an application such as a M16 bolt. 9310 is a steel typically used for gears, cams and things of that nature while Carpenter 158 or P6 tool steel is a plastic injection mold steel. 9310 is easier to machine and is more dimensionally stable in the heat treat process, this equates to better made parts. 
The extractors are Mil-Spec made from a solid piece of 4140. All of our springs made to the Mil-Spec out of 17-7PH Stainless steel not the cheaper music wire some companies use. We use a one-piece 316 Stainless steel helicial ring on all of our bolts. The cam pin and firing pin are standard mil-spec parts.
